\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

So the orderings of the 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

-tuple of polynomials matters.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Elimination) Divide 
\begin_inset Formula $f=z^{2}x+zy+yx^{3}+x$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}=y-x^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}=z-x^{3}$
\end_inset

 using lex order with 
\begin_inset Formula $z>y>x$
\end_inset

.
 Then switch the ordering of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
