\begin_layout Section*
Monomial Ideals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 An ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
monomial ideal 
\series default
if there is a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}^{n}$
\end_inset

 (possibly infinite) such that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 consists of all polynomials which are finite sums of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{\alpha\in A}h_{\alpha}x^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\alpha}\in K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we write 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle x^{\alpha}\mid\alpha\in A\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 An example of a monomial ideal is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle x^{4}y^{2},x^{3}y^{4},x^{2}y^{5}\rangle\subseteq K[x,y]$
\end_inset

.
 A nontrivial example of a monomial ideal is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $J=\langle f_{1},f_{2},f_{3},f_{4}\rangle=\langle x^{2}+x^{2}y^{3},-x^{2}y^{3}+y^{3},x^{4},y^{6}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 It's easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $J\subset\langle x^{2},y^{3}\rangle$
\end_inset

, let's show the reverse inclusion.
 Write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x^{2} & =f_{1}-x^{2}f_{2}-y^{3}f_{3}\\
y^{3} & =f_{1}+y^{3}f_{2}-x^{2}f_{4}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x^{2},y^{3}\rangle\subset J$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{monomialdivisible}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle x^{\alpha}\mid\alpha\in A\rangle$
\end_inset

 be a monomial ideal.
 Then a monomial 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 lies in 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in A$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\beta}\in I$
\end_inset

 by the definition of the ideal.
 Conversely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\beta}\in I$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\beta}=\sum_{i=1}^{s}h_{i}x^{\alpha(i)}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}\in K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(i)\in A$
\end_inset

.
 If we expand each 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}$
\end_inset

 as a sum of terms, we obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{\beta}=\sum_{i=1}^{s}h_{i}x^{\alpha(i)}=\sum_{i=1}^{s}\left(\sum_{j}c_{i,j}x^{\beta(i,j)}\right)x^{\alpha(i)}=\sum_{i,j}c_{i,j}x^{\beta(i,j)}x^{\alpha(i)}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After collecting terms of the same multidegree, every term on the right
 side of the equation is divisible by some 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\alpha(i)}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, the left side 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 must have the same property.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{dicksonlemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Dickson's Lemma.) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle x^{\alpha}\mid\alpha\in A\rangle$
\end_inset

 be a monomial ideal.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle x^{\alpha(1)},\dots,x^{\alpha(s)}\rangle$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(1),\dots,\alpha(s)\in A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (By induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, the number of variables.) If 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is generated by the monomials 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in A\subseteq\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}$
\end_inset

 is well-ordered, there exists a smallest element of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, call it 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\leq\alpha$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in A$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 divides all other generators 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 From here, it follows 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle x^{\beta}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now assume 
\begin_inset Formula $n>1$
\end_inset

 and that the theorem is true for 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

.
 We will write the variables as 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1},y$
\end_inset

, so that monomials in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1},y]$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\alpha}y^{m}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{n-1})\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}^{n-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1},y]$
\end_inset

 is a monomial ideal.
 To find generators for 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $J=I:y^{\infty}\cap K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1}]$
\end_inset

 be the ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1}]$
\end_inset

 generated by the monomials 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\alpha}y^{m}\in I$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 From the induction hypothesis, we obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 is finitely generated, say 
\begin_inset Formula $J=\langle x^{\alpha(1)},\dots,x^{\alpha(s)}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 between 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\alpha(i)}y^{m_{i}}\in I$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{i}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 be the largest 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 between 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m-1$
\end_inset

, consider the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\ell}=I:y^{\ell}\cap K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1}]$
\end_inset

 generated by the monomials 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\beta}y^{\ell}\in I$
\end_inset

.
 One can think of 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\ell}$
\end_inset

 as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

slice
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 generated by monomials containing 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 exactly to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

th power.
 Clearly we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J=J_{m}\supset J_{m-1}\cdots\supset J_{1}\supset J_{0}=I\cap K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1}].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using our inductive hypothesis again, 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\ell}$
\end_inset

 has a finite generating set of monomials, say 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\ell}=\langle x^{\alpha_{\ell}(1)},\dots,x^{\alpha_{\ell}(s_{\ell})}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is generated by the monomials in the following list: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mbox{from }J_{0}: & x^{\alpha_{0}(1)},\dots,x^{\alpha_{0}(s_{0})},\\
\mbox{from }J_{1}: & x^{\alpha_{1}(1)}y,\dots,x^{\alpha_{1}(s_{1})}y,\\
\vdots\\
\mbox{from }J_{m-1}: & x^{\alpha_{m-1}(1)}y^{m-1},\dots,x^{\alpha_{m-1}(s_{m-1})}y^{m-1},\\
\mbox{from }J: & x^{\alpha(1)}y^{m},\dots,x^{\alpha(s)}y^{m}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First note that every monomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is divisible by one on the list.
 To see why, let 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\alpha}y^{p}\in I$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $p\geq m$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\alpha}y^{p}$
\end_inset

 is divisible by some 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\alpha(i)}y^{m}$
\end_inset

 by the construction of 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

: Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\alpha}y^{p}\in I$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\alpha}\in J$
\end_inset

.
 So by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{monomialdivisible})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is divisible by some 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\alpha(i)}$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $p\geq m$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\alpha}y^{p}$
\end_inset

 is divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\alpha(i)}y^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, if 
\begin_inset Formula $p\leq m-1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\alpha}y^{p}$
\end_inset

 is divisible by some 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\alpha_{p}(j)}y^{p}$
\end_inset

 by the construction of 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{p}$
\end_inset

, for the same reason as above.
 It follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{monomialdivisible})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that the above monomials generate an ideal having the same monomials as
 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, and this forces the ideals to be the same.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let's illustrate how the proof works when 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle x^{4},x^{3}y^{2}z,x^{2}yz^{3},xy^{3}z^{2},y^{4},z^{4}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 be the ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[y,z]$
\end_inset

 generated by the monomials 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{m_{1}}z^{m_{2}}$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{m}y^{m_{1}}z^{m_{1}}\in I$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m\geq0$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\ell}$
\end_inset

 be defined as in the theorem above.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
J_{0} & =\langle y^{4},z^{4}\rangle\\
J_{1} & =\langle y^{4},z^{4},y^{3}z^{2}\rangle\\
J_{2} & =\langle y^{4},z^{4},y^{3}z^{2},yz^{3}\rangle\\
J_{3} & =\langle y^{4},z^{4},yz^{3},y^{2}z\rangle\\
J & =\langle1\rangle.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The theorem then tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is generated by the monomials in the following list:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mbox{from }J: & x^{4}\\
\mbox{from }J_{0}: & y^{4},z^{4}\\
\mbox{from }J_{1}: & y^{4}x,z^{4}x,y^{3}z^{2}x\\
\mbox{from }J_{2}: & y^{4}x^{2},z^{4}x^{2},y^{3}z^{2}x^{2},yz^{3}x^{2}\\
\mbox{from }J_{3}: & y^{4}x^{3},z^{4}x^{3},yz^{3}x^{3},y^{2}zx^{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Hilbert Basis Theorem and Grobner Bases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 be an ideal other than 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0\}$
\end_inset

, and fix a monomial ordering on 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(I)$
\end_inset

 the set of leading terms of nonzero elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{LT}(I)=\{cx^{\alpha}\mid\mbox{there exists }f\in I\setminus\{0\}\mbox{ with LT}(f)=cx^{\alpha}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mbox{LT}(I)\rangle$
\end_inset

 be the ideal generated by the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(I)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mbox{LT}(I)\rangle$
\end_inset

 is clearly a monomial ideal, hence it is finitely generated.
 That is, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},\dots,g_{t}\in I$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(I)=\langle\mbox{LT}(g_{1}),\dots,\mbox{LT}(g_{t})\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 If we are given an arbitrary finite generating set for 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle f_{1},\dots,f_{s}\rangle$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mbox{LT}(f_{1}),\dots,\mbox{LT}(f_{s})\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mbox{LT}(I)\rangle$
\end_inset

 may be 
\emph on
different 
\emph default
ideals.
 To see this, consider the following example.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle f_{1},f_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}=x^{3}-2xy$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}=x^{2}y-2y^{2}+x$
\end_inset

, and use grlex ordering on monomials in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x,y]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\cdot(x^{2}y-2y^{2}+x)-y\cdot(x^{3}-2xy)=x^{2},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
so that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}=\mbox{LT}(x^{2})\in\langle\mbox{LT}(I)\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 However 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}$
\end_inset

 is not divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(f_{1})=x^{3}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(f_{2})=x^{2}y$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}\notin\langle\mbox{LT}(f_{1}),\mbox{LT}(f_{2})\rangle$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Fix a monomial order on the polynomial ring 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 A finite subset 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\{g_{1},\dots,g_{t}\}$
\end_inset

 of an ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 different from 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0\}$
\end_inset

 is said to be a 
\series bold
Grobner basis 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle\mbox{LT}(g_{1}),\dots,\mbox{LT}(g_{t})\rangle=\langle\mbox{LT}(I)\rangle.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The next theorem justifies our use of the word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

basis
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Grobner basis
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Hilbert Basis Theorem).
 Every ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 has a finite generating set.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle g_{1},\dots,g_{t}\rangle$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},\dots,g_{t}\in I$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\{0\}$
\end_inset

, we take our generating set to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0\}$
\end_inset

, which is certainly finite.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 contains some nonzero polynomial, then a generating set 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},\dots,g_{t}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 can be constructed as follows.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We first select one particular monomial order to use in the division algorithm
 and in computing leading terms.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 has an ideal of leading terms 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mbox{LT}(I)\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mbox{LT}(I)\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a monomial ideal, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},\dots,g_{t}\in I$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mbox{LT}(I)\rangle=\langle\mbox{LT}(g_{1}),\dots,\mbox{LT}(g_{t})\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle g_{1},\dots,g_{t}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in I$
\end_inset

 be any polynomial.
 If we apply the division algorithm to divide 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $(g_{1},\dots,g_{t})$
\end_inset

, then we get an expression of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f=q_{1}g_{1}+\cdots+q_{t}g_{t}+r
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where no term of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is divisible by any of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(g_{1}),\dots,\mbox{LT}(g_{t})$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, note that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r=f-q_{1}g_{1}-\cdots-q_{t}g_{t}\in I.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $r\neq0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(r)\in\mbox{LT}(I)=\langle\mbox{LT}(g_{1}),\dots,\mbox{LT}(g_{t})\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(r)$
\end_inset

 must be divisible by some 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(g_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 This contradicts what it means to be a remainder, and, consequently, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 must be zero.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f=q_{1}g_{1}+\cdots q_{t}g_{t}+0\in\langle g_{1},\dots,g_{t}\rangle,
\]

\end_inset

 which shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq\langle g_{1},\dots,g_{t}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 The reverse inclusion is trivial.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Properties of Grobner Bases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 be an ideal and let 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\{g_{1},\dots,g_{t}\}$
\end_inset

 be a Grobner basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 Then given 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

, there is a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 with the following two properties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
No term of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is divisible by any of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(g_{1}),\dots,\mbox{LT}(g_{t})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There is 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in I$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f=g+r$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is the remainder on division of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 no matter how the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 are listed when using the division algorithm.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The division algorithm gives 
\begin_inset Formula $f=q_{1}g_{1}+\cdots+q_{t}g_{t}+r$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $(1)$
\end_inset

.
 We can also satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $(2)$
\end_inset

 by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $g=q_{1}g_{1}+\cdots+q_{t}g_{t}\in I$
\end_inset

.
 This proves the existence of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To prove uniqueness, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f=g+r=g'+r'$
\end_inset

 satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $(1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(2)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $r-r'=g'-g\in I$
\end_inset

, so that if 
\begin_inset Formula $r\neq r'$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(r-r')\in\langle\mbox{LT}(I)\rangle=\langle\mbox{LT}(g_{1}),\cdots,\mbox{LT}(g_{t})\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(r-r')$
\end_inset

 is divisible by some 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(g_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 This is impossible since no term of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $r'$
\end_inset

 is divisible by one of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(g_{1}),\dots\mbox{LT}(g_{t})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $r-r'$
\end_inset

 must be zero, and uniqueness is proved.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We will write 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{f}^{F}$
\end_inset

 for the remainder on division of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 by the ordered 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

-tuple 
\begin_inset Formula $F=(f_{1},\dots,f_{s})$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a Grobner basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle f_{1},\dots,f_{s}\rangle$
\end_inset

, then we can regard 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 as a set (without any particular order).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-polynomials
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We will write 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{f}^{F}$
\end_inset

 for the remainder on division of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 by the ordered 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

-tuple 
\begin_inset Formula $F=(f_{1},\dots,f_{s})$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a Gröbner basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle f_{1},\dots,f_{s}\rangle$
\end_inset

, then we can regard 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 as a set (without any particular order).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For instance, with 
\begin_inset Formula $F=(x^{2}y-y^{2},x^{4}y^{2}-y^{2})\subseteq K[x,y]$
\end_inset

, using the lex order, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{x^{5}y}^{F}=xy^{3}
\]

\end_inset

 since the division algorithm yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{5}y=(x^{3}+xy)(x^{2}y-y^{2})+0\cdot(x^{4}y^{2}-y^{2})+xy^{3}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The obstruction to 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f_{1},\dots,f_{s}\}$
\end_inset

 being a Grobner basis is the possible occurence polynomial combinatios
 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 whose leading terms are not in the ideal generated by the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(f_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 One way this can occur is if the leading terms in a suitable combination
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ax^{\alpha}f_{i}-bx^{\beta}f_{j}
\]

\end_inset

 cancel, leaving only smaller terms.
 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $ax^{\alpha}f_{i}-bx^{\beta}f_{j}\in I$
\end_inset

, so its leading term is in 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mbox{LT}(I)\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 be nonzero polynomials.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{multdeg}(f)=\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{multdeg}(g)=\beta$
\end_inset

, then let 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=(\gamma_{1},\dots,\gamma_{n})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{i}=\mbox{max}(\alpha_{i},\beta_{i})$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 We call 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
least common multiple 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LM}(f)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LM}(g)$
\end_inset

, written 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\gamma}=\mbox{lcm}(\mbox{LM}(f),\mbox{LM}(g))$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
polynomial 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is the combination
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S(f,g)=\frac{x^{\gamma}}{\mbox{LT}(f)}\cdot f-\frac{x^{\gamma}}{\mbox{LT}(g)}\cdot g.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{buchbergercriterion}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Buchberger's Criterion).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be a polynomial ideal.
 Then a basis 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\{g_{1},\dots,g_{t}\}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a Gröbner basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 if and only if for all pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

, the remainder on division of 
\begin_inset Formula $S(g_{i},g_{j})$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is zero.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{grobnerexample}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}[x,y]$
\end_inset

 with grlex order, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle f_{1},f_{2}\rangle=\langle x^{3}-2xy,x^{2}y-2y^{2}+x\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f_{1},f_{2}\}$
\end_inset

 is not a Gröbner basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(S(f_{1},f_{2}))=-x^{2}\notin\langle\mbox{LT}(f_{1}),\mbox{LT}(f_{2})\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we should add in 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{3}=-x^{2}$
\end_inset

 into our generating set.
 So setting 
\begin_inset Formula $F=(f_{1},f_{2},f_{3})$
\end_inset

, we compute 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
S(f_{1},f_{2}) & =f_{3},\mbox{ so}\\
\overline{S(f_{1},f_{2})}^{F} & =0,\\
S(f_{1},f_{3}) & =-2xy,\mbox{ but}\\
\overline{S(f_{1},f_{3})}^{F} & =-2xy\neq0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, we must add 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{4}=-2xy$
\end_inset

 to our generating set.
 If we let 
\begin_inset Formula $F=(f_{1},f_{2},f_{3},f_{4})$
\end_inset

, then we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\overline{S(f_{1},f_{2})}^{F} & =\overline{S(f_{1},f_{3})}^{F}=0,\\
S(f_{1},f_{4}) & =-2xy^{2},\mbox{ so}\\
\overline{S(f_{1},f_{4})}^{F} & =0,\\
\overline{S(f_{2},f_{3})}^{F} & =-2y^{2}+x,\mbox{ but}\\
\overline{S(f_{2},f_{3})}^{F} & =-2y^{2}+x\neq0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence, we must also add 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{5}=-2y^{2}+x$
\end_inset

 to our generating set.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $F=(f_{1},f_{2},f_{3},f_{4},f_{5})$
\end_inset

, one can compute that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{S(f_{i},f_{j})}^{F}=0\mbox{ for all }1\leq i<j\leq5.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{buchbergercriterion})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, it follows that a grlex Gröbner basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{f_{1},f_{2},f_{3},f_{4},f_{5}\}=\{x^{3}-2xy,x^{2}y-2y^{2}+x,-x^{2},-2xy,-2y^{2}+x\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{buchbergeralgorithm}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Buchberger's Algorithm).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle f_{1},\dots,f_{s}\rangle\neq\{0\}$
\end_inset

 be a polynomial ideal.
 Then a Gröbner basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 can be constructed in a finite number of steps by the described algorithm.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Why does this algorithm terminate? We need to consider what happens after
 each pass through the main loop.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 consists of 
\begin_inset Formula $G'$
\end_inset

 (the old 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

) together with the nonzero remainders of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-polynomials of elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $G'$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle\mbox{LT}(G')\rangle\subseteq\langle\mbox{LT}(G)\rangle\label{eq:successive}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $G'\subseteq G$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, if 
\begin_inset Formula $G'\neq G$
\end_inset

, we claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mbox{LT}(G')\rangle$
\end_inset

 is strictly smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mbox{LT}(G)\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, suppose that a nonzero remainder 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 of and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-polynomial has been adjoined to 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is a remainder on division by 
\begin_inset Formula $G'$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(r)$
\end_inset

 is not divisible by the leading terms of elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $G'$
\end_inset

, and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(r)\notin\langle\mbox{LT}(G')\rangle$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{monomialdivisible})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Yet 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(r)\in\langle\mbox{LT}(G)\rangle$
\end_inset

, which proves our claim.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:successive})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mbox{LT}(G')\rangle$
\end_inset

 from successive iterations of the loop form an ascending chain of ideals
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the Ascending Chain Condition implies that after a finite number
 of iterations the chain will stabilize, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mbox{LT}(G')\rangle=\langle\mbox{LT}(G)\rangle$
\end_inset

 must happen eventually.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Gröbner bases computed using the algorithm of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{buchbergeralgorithm})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 are often bigger than necessary.
 We can eliminate some unneeded generators by using the following fact.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{eliminate}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a Gröbner basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in G$
\end_inset

 be a polynomial such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(p)\in\langle\mbox{LT}(G\setminus\{p\})\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $G\setminus\{p\}$
\end_inset

 is also a Gröbner basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mbox{LT}(G)\rangle=\langle\mbox{LT}(I)\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(p)\in\langle\mbox{LT}(G\setminus\{p\})\rangle$
\end_inset

, then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mbox{LT}(G\setminus\{p\})\rangle=\langle\mbox{LT}(G)\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 By definition, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $G\setminus\{p\}$
\end_inset

 is also a Gröbner basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

By adjusting constants to make all leading coefficients equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and removing any 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(p)\in\langle\mbox{LT}(G\setminus\{p\}\rangle$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, we arrive at what we will call a 
\series bold
minimal Gröbner basis
\series default
.
 We can construct a minimal Gröbner basis for a given nonzero ideal by applying
 the algorithm of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{buchbergeralgorithm})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and then using 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{eliminate})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to eliminate any unneeded generators that might have been included.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To illustrate this procedure, we return to the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 studied in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Example~(
\backslash
ref{grobnerexample})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Using grlex order, we found the Gröbner basis 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f_{1} & =x^{3}-2xy,\\
f_{2} & =x^{2}y-2y^{2}+x,\\
f_{3} & =-x^{2},\\
f_{4} & =-2xy,\\
f_{5} & =-2y^{2}+x.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since some of the leading coefficients are different from 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, the first step is to multiply the generators by suitable constants to
 make this true.
 Then note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(f_{1})=x^{3}=-x\cdot\mbox{LT}(f_{3})$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{eliminate})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we can dispense with 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 in the minimal Gröbner basis.
 Similarly, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(f_{2})=x^{2}y=-(1/2)x\cdot\mbox{LT}(f_{4})$
\end_inset

, we can also eliminate 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 There are no further cases where the leading term of a generator divides
 the leading term of another generator.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\tilde{f}_{3} & =x^{2},\\
\tilde{f}_{4} & =xy,\\
\tilde{f}_{5} & =y^{2}-(1/2)x
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 is a minimal Gröbner basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

When 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a minimal Gröbner basis, the leading terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(p)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in G$
\end_inset

, form the unique minimal basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mbox{LT}(I)\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Unfortunately, the original ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 may have many minimal Gröbner bases.
 For example, in the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 considered above, it is easy to check that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\tilde{f}_{3} & =x^{2}+axy,\\
\tilde{f}_{4} & =xy,\\
\tilde{f}_{5} & =y^{2}-(1/2)x
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is also a minimal Gröbner basis, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 is any constant.
 Thus, we can produce infinitely many minimal Gröbner bases.
 Fortunately, we can single out one minimal basis that is better than others.
 The definition is as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
reduced Gröbner basis 
\series default
for a polynomial ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a Gröbner basis 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 such that: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LC}(p)=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in G$
\end_inset

, no monomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 lies in 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mbox{LT}(G\setminus\{p\}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To conclude this section, we will indicate briefly some of the connections
 between Buchberger's algorithm and Gaussian elimination.
 Consider the system of linear equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x-2y-z-w & =0,\\
3x-6y-2z & =0,\\
2x-4y+4w & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve it, we apply Gaussian elimination to the coefficient matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{pmatrix}1 & -2 & -1 & -1\\
3 & -6 & -2 & 0\\
2 & -4 & 0 & 4
\end{pmatrix}\to\begin{pmatrix}1 & -2 & -1 & -1\\
0 & 0 & 1 & 3\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 0
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The resulting matrix is in row echelon form, but to get it into 
\emph on
reduced 
\emph default
row echelon form, we need to make sure that each leading 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 is the only nonzero entry in its column.
 This leads to the matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{pmatrix}1 & -2 & 0 & 2\\
0 & 0 & 1 & 3\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 0
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To translate the computations into algebra, let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle3x-6y-2z,2x-4y+4w,x-2y-z-w\rangle\subseteq K[x,y,z,w]$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the original system of equations.
 We will use lex order with 
\begin_inset Formula $x>y>z>w$
\end_inset

.
 Then the row echelon form matrix gives a minimal Gröbner basis 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle x-2y-z-w,z+3w\rangle$
\end_inset

 and the reduced row echelon form gives the reduced Gröbner basis 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle x-2y+2w,z+3w\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Recall from linear algebra that every matrix can be put in reduced row
 echelon form in a unique way.
 This can be viewed as a special case of the uniqueness of reduced Gröbner
 bases.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Applications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider the parametric curve 
\begin_inset Formula $V:$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x & =t^{4}\\
y & =t^{3}\\
z & =t^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 The image below shows a piece of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}
\backslash
begin{axis}[view={30}{30},] 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot3[domain=-5:5, samples =60, samples y=0, color=red]({x^4 }, {x^3
 }, {x^2 });
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{axis}
\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We compute a Gröbner basis 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle f_{1},f_{2},f_{3}\rangle=\langle t^{4}-x,t^{3}-y,t^{2}-z\rangle$
\end_inset

 with respect to lex order in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}[t,x,y,z]$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $t>x>y>z$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $F=(f_{1},f_{2},f_{3})$
\end_inset

, we compute 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
S(f_{1},f_{2}) & =ty-x,\mbox{ but}\\
\overline{S(f_{1},f_{2})}^{F} & =ty-x.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, we must add 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{4}=ty-x$
\end_inset

 to our generating set.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $F=(f_{1},f_{2},f_{3},f_{4})$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
S(f_{2},f_{3}) & =tz-y,\mbox{ but}\\
\overline{S(f_{2},f_{3})}^{F} & =tz-y.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus, we must add 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{5}=tz-y$
\end_inset

 to our generating set.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $F=(f_{1},f_{2},f_{3},f_{4},f_{5})$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
S(f_{1},f_{3}) & =t^{2}z-x,\mbox{ but}\\
\overline{S(f_{1},f_{3})}^{F} & =-x+z^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus, we must add 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{6}=-x+z^{2}$
\end_inset

 to our generating set.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $F=(f_{1},f_{2},f_{3},f_{4},f_{5},f_{6})$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
S(f_{4},f_{5}) & =xz-y^{2},\mbox{ but}\\
\overline{S(f_{2},f_{3})}^{F} & =-y^{2}+z^{3}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus, we must add 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{7}=-y^{2}+z^{3}$
\end_inset

 to our generating set.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $F=(f_{1},f_{2},f_{3},f_{4},f_{5},f_{6},f_{7})$
\end_inset

, one can compute that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{S(f_{i},f_{j})}^{F}=0\mbox{ for all }1\leq i<j\leq7.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f_{1},f_{2},f_{3},f_{4},f_{5},f_{6},f_{7}\}$
\end_inset

 forms a Gröbner basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 One can compute that the minimal reduced Gröbner basis is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G=\{t^{2}-z,ty-z^{2},tz-y,x-z^{2},y^{2}-z^{3}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The last two polynomials depend only on 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z$
\end_inset

, so they define an affine variety of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}^{3}$
\end_inset

 containing our curve 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Since there are two equations, we guess that they define a curve in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 The remaining question to answer is whether 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\mathbf{V}(x-z^{2},y^{2}-z^{3})$
\end_inset

, that is, is 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 the entire intersection of the two surfaces 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(x,y,z)\in K^{3}\mid x-z^{2}=0\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(x,y,z)\in K^{3}\mid y^{2}-z^{3}=0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Might there be other curves (or even surfaces) in the intersection? The
 answer is no.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider the tangent surface of the twisted cubic in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 The surface is parametrized by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x & =t+u,\\
y & =t^{2}+2tu,\\
z & =t^{3}+3t^{2}u.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We use singular to compute a Gröbner basis 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 for this ideal relative to the lex order defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $t>u>x>y>z$
\end_inset

.
 The code for this is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
ring A = 0,(t,u,x,y,z),lp; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
ideal I = x-t-u, y-t2-2tu, z-t3+3t2u;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
groebner(I);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
_[1]=20x3z+15x2y2-18xyz-16y3-z2 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
_[2]=20uy3-2uz2+20x2yz-5xy3-2xz2-13y2z 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
_[3]=2uxz+4uy2+2x2z-xy2-yz 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
_[4]=5uxy+uz-5x2y+xz+4y2 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
_[5]=10ux2-4uy-10x3+9xy+z 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
_[6]=u2-x2+y 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
_[7]=t+u-x 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Singular outputs 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\{f_{1},f_{2},f_{3},f_{4},f_{5},f_{6},f_{7}\}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f_{1} & =20x^{3}z+15x^{2}y^{2}-18xyz-16y^{3}-z^{2},\\
f_{2} & =20uy^{3}-2uz^{2}+20x^{2}yz-5xy^{3}-2xz^{2}-13y^{2}z,\\
f_{3} & =2uxz+4uy^{2}+2x^{2}z-xy^{2}-yz\\
f_{4} & =5uxy+uz-5x^{2}y+xz+4y^{2}\\
f_{5} & =10ux^{2}-4uy-10x^{3}+9xy+z\\
f_{6} & =u^{2}-x^{2}+y\\
f_{7} & =t+u-x
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 is the only polynomial involving only 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z$
\end_inset

 terms.
 The variety 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\mathbf{V}(f_{1})$
\end_inset

 defined by this equation is a surface containing the tangent surface to
 the twisted cubic.
 However, it is possible that 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is strictly bigger than the tangent surface, i.e.
 there may be solutions to 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}=0$
\end_inset

 that do not correspond to points on the tangent surface.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Algorithmic Computations in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]/I$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{remainderrep}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Fix a monomial ordering on 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 be an ideal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Every 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 is congruent modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 to a unique polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 which is a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-linear combination of monomials in the complement of 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mbox{LT}(I)\rangle$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x^{\alpha}\mid x^{\alpha}\notin\langle\mbox{LT}(I)\rangle\}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

linearly independent modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 i.e., if we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{\alpha}c_{\alpha}x^{\alpha}\equiv0\mbox{ mod }I,
\]

\end_inset

 where the 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 are all in the complement of 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mbox{LT}(I)\rangle$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\alpha}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a Gröbner basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 By the division algorithm, the remainder 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\overline{f}^{G}$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $f=q+r$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $f-r=q\in I$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $f\equiv r\mbox{ mod }I$
\end_inset

.
 The division algorithm also tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-linear combination of the monomials 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\alpha}\notin\langle\mbox{LT}(I)\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a Gröbner basis, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is also unique.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{\alpha}c_{\alpha}x^{\alpha}\equiv0\mbox{ mod }I,
\]

\end_inset

 where the 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 are all in the complement of 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mbox{LT}(I)\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{\alpha}c_{\alpha}x^{\alpha}=\sum_{\beta}d_{\beta}x^{\beta}
\]

\end_inset

 where the 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 are in 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mbox{LT}(I)\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Since the set of all monomials forms a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-basis, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\alpha}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle xy^{3}-x^{2},x^{3}y^{2}-y\rangle$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[x,y]$
\end_inset

 and use graded lex order.
 We find that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G=\{x^{3}y^{2}-y,x^{4}-y^{2},xy^{3}-x^{2},y^{4}-xy\}
\]

\end_inset

is a Gröbner basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mbox{LT}(I)\rangle=\langle x^{3}y^{2},x^{4},xy^{3},y^{4}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Given any 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathbb{R}[x,y]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{remainderrep})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, implies that the remainder 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{f}^{G}$
\end_inset

 will be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-linear combination of the 
\begin_inset Formula $12$
\end_inset

 monomials: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1,x,x^{2},x^{3},y,xy,x^{2}y,x^{3}y,y^{2},xy^{2},x^{2}y^{2},y^{3}.
\]

\end_inset

Note that in this case the remainders all belong to a finite-dimensional
 vector subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[x,y]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We may also ask what happens if we use a different monomial order in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[x,y]$
\end_inset

 with the same ideal.
 If we use lex order instead of grlex, with the variables ordered 
\begin_inset Formula $y>x$
\end_inset

, we find that a Gröbner basis in this case is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G=\{y-x^{7},x^{12}-x^{2}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence, for this monomial order, 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mbox{LT}(I)\rangle=\langle y,x^{12}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, for every 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathbb{R}[x,y]$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{f}\in\mbox{Span}(1,x,x^{2},\dots,x^{12})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Normal Forms and Standard Bases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $>$
\end_inset

 be a fixed monomial ordering and let, in this section, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R=K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]_{>}
\]

\end_inset

be the localization of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x]=K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $>$
\end_inset

.
 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $R=S_{>}^{-1}K[x]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{>}=\{u\in K[x]\backslash\{0\}\mid\mbox{LM}(u)=1\}$
\end_inset

, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $R=K[x]$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $>$
\end_inset

 is global and 
\begin_inset Formula $R=K[x]_{\langle x\rangle}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $>$
\end_inset

 is local.
 In any case, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 may be considered as a subring of the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $K[[x]]$
\end_inset

 of formal power series.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn1}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset R$
\end_inset

 be an ideal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A finite set 
\begin_inset Formula $G\subset R$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
standard basis 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G\subset I\quad\mbox{and}\quad L(I)=L(G).
\]

\end_inset

 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a standard basis if the leading monomials of the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 generate the leading ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, or in other words, if for any 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in I\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LM}(g)\mid\mbox{LM}(f)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $>$
\end_inset

 is global, a standard basis is also called a 
\series bold
Gröbner basis
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If we just say that 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a standard basis, we mean that 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a standard basis of the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle G\rangle_{R}$
\end_inset

 generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn2}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G\subset R$
\end_inset

 be any subset.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
interreduced 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $0\notin G$
\end_inset

 and if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LM}(g)\not\mid\mbox{LM}(f)$
\end_inset

 for any two elements 
\begin_inset Formula $f\neq g$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 An interreduced standard basis is also called 
\series bold
minimal
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $f\in R$
\end_inset

 is called (
\series bold
completely
\series default
) 
\series bold
reduced 
\series default
with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 if no monomial of the power series expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $L(G)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is called (
\series bold
completely
\series default
) 
\series bold
reduced 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is interreduced and if, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LC}(g)=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{tail}(g)$
\end_inset

 is completely reduced with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example1}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}[x,y]$
\end_inset

 with grlex order, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle x^{3}-2xy,x^{2}y-2y^{2}+x\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 A Gröbner basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\{f_{1},f_{2},f_{3},f_{4},f_{5}\}$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f_{1} & =x^{3}-2xy\\
f_{2} & =x^{2}y-2y^{2}+x\\
f_{3} & =-x^{2}\\
f_{4} & =-2xy\\
f_{5} & =-2y^{2}+x.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is not completely reduced.
 Since some of the leading coefficients are different from 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, the first step is to multiply the generators by suitable constants to
 make this true.
 Then note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LM}(f_{3})\mid\mbox{LM}(f_{1})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn3}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 denote the set of all finite lists 
\begin_inset Formula $G\subset R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{NF}:R\times\mathcal{G}\to R,\qquad(f,G)\mapsto f^{G}
\]

\end_inset

is called a 
\series bold
normal form 
\series default
on 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $G\in\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in R$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $0^{G}=0,$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $f^{G}\neq0$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LM}(f^{G})\notin L(G)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\{g_{1},\dots,g_{s}\}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f-f^{G}$
\end_inset

 has a 
\series bold
standard representation
\series default
, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f-f^{G}=\sum_{i=1}^{s}a_{i}g_{i},\quad a_{i}\in R,\quad s\geq0,
\]

\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LM}(\sum_{i=1}^{s}a_{i}g_{i})\geq\mbox{LM}(a_{i}g_{i})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}g_{i}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{NF}$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
reduced normal form
\series default
, if, moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{G}$
\end_inset

 is reduced with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In the case of a global ordering, for any polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and any ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, there is a unique normal form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{NF}(f\mid I)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, such that no monomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{NF}(f\mid I)$
\end_inset

 is in the leading ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $L(I)$
\end_inset

.
 This can be used to decide, for instance, whether 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is in the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 In the general case, the above property turns out to be too strong.
 Hence, the requirements for a normal form have to be weakened.
 For instance, for the decision whether a polynomial is in an ideal or not,
 only the leading term of the normal form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{NF}(f\mid I)$
\end_inset

 is important.
 Thus, for this purpose, it is enough to require that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{NF}(f\mid I)$
\end_inset

 is either 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 or has a leading term, which is not in 
\begin_inset Formula $L(I)$
\end_inset

.
 After weakening the requirements, there is no more uniqueness statement
 for the normal form.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_body
\end_document
